 and that During the Crossing from Singapore to Hong Kong -- tIn which Phileas Fogg, Passepartout, and Fix go about their Separate Business -- tWhere Passepartout Grows Extremely Concerned for his Master and What Comes of it -- tIn Which Fix Makes Direct Contact with Phileas Fogg -- tWhere the Tankadère’s Skipper is in Real Danger of Losing his £200 Bonus -- tWhere Passepartout Finds that Even Halfway Around the World, it’s Wise to have a Little Money in your Pocket -- tIn Which Passepartout’s Nose gets Outlandishly Long -- tDuring Which they Cross the Whole Pacific Ocean -- tWhich Gives a Brief Glimpse of San Francisco at Election Time -- tIn Which we Ride an Express Train on the Pacific Railroad -- tDuring Which Passepartout Takes a Course in Mormon History at a Speed of Twenty Miles per Hour -- tIn Which Passepartout can’t get Anybody to Use his Head -- tWhich will Describe Assorted Incidents that are Met with only on Union Railroads -- tIn Which Phileas Fogg Simply does what’s Right -- tWhere Inspector Fix Behaves in Phileas Fogg’s Best Interests -- tIn which Phileas Fogg Grapples with Misfortune -- tIn which Phileas Fogg Rises to the Occasion -- tWhich gives Passepartout the Chance to Crack an Outrageous but Possibly Original Joke -- tIn which Passepartout doesn’t Need to be told Twice to do what his Master Says -- tWhere Shares in Phileas Fogg are Back at a Premium on the Stock Market -- tWhich Demonstrates that Phileas Fogg didn’t Gain a Thing by Going Around the World— Other than Happiness -- tTextual Notes -- tRecommended Reading0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPart manhunt, part love story, part social satire, but mostly a race against the clock, Around the World in 80 Days is Jules Verne's most rollicking novel. When Phileas Fogg, a wealthy British gentleman who lives his life "with mathemetical predictability," bets the fellow members of his club £20,000 that he can circle the earth in just eighty days, he and his new valet, Passepartout, set out on a whirlwind tour of the globe that will challenge their luck, their wits, and their wallets. En route they ride an elephant smack into an exotic murder cult, steer an undersized sailboat through rampaging storms, and outrun sharp-shooting Sioux, man-eating wolves, and Scotland Yard's dimmest detective—only to see everything go hopelessly haywire until Verne springs the slyest of surprise endings. It's one of the planet's favorite thrillers, and Frederick Paul Walter's reader-friendly translation captures its roguish wit and humor, packages its Americana with exceptional accuracy (one-fourth of the tale takes place in the United States), and is complete and unabridged down to the smallest substantive detail.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aVoyages around the worldvFiction. 4aGeneral Interest : Fiction. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aWalter, Frederick Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143844680640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438446806423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438446806/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles